4d8.title: Morphism
4d8.text:
A morphism is the abstract representation of a [-relation] between [-mathematical_object mathematical objects].

Usually, it is used to refer to [-functions] mapping element of one set to another, but it may represent a more general notion of a relation in [-4c7].

##Isomorphisms##
To understand a morphism, it is easier to first understand the concept of an [-4f4]. Two mathematical structures (say two [-3gd groups]) are called **isomorphic** if they are indistinguishable using the information of the language and theory under consideration. 

## Embeddings ##
An **embedding**, **inclusion map** or **injective morphism** is a morphism which maps a structure into an isomorphic copy of itself inside a 'larger' structure. 

For example, consider the set $\{1,2,3\}$. It can be embedded into $\{1,2,3,4\}$ by taking $1 \mapsto 1$, $2 \mapsto 2$ and $3 \mapsto 3$. However, it can also be embedded in $\{a,b,c,d\}$ by $1\mapsto a$, $2 \mapsto b$ and $3 \mapsto c$. In fact, the order doesn't matter, so $1\mapsto d$, $2 \mapsto a$, $3 \mapsto c$ would also work. 

## General Morphisms ##
A morphism which is a function must be a function which *preserves* the structure of what it is mapping, in the sense that the image under the function of its [-domain_of_a_function domain] must 'act like' the domain.

In terms of [-concrete] [3gx algebraic structures] and [-relational_structure relational structures] such as [-3gd groups], [-ring rings], [-3rb posets], and [-graph graphs], the function must [-preservation_of_structure preserve] the relevant constants, operations and relations.

If the domain is a [-topological_space topological space], its image under $f$ must be 'at most as seperable' as it was, in the sense that if any part of the image is open, its [-preimage] under $f$ must be open.
